'''Krystyna Kurczab-Redlich''' (born 1954) is a [[Poland|Polish]] journalist and author.

As a correspondent in [[Russia]] for the Polish media, she has written documentary films on [[Chechnya]]<ref name=romance>{{cite web| url = http://kyivweekly.com.ua/pulse/persona/2010/10/25/151517.html | title = Krystyna Kurczab-Redlich Russian romance | accessdate = 2010-10-31 | date = 2010-10-25 | publisher = ''Kyiv Weekly''}}</ref> investigating alleged human rights abuses by the [[Russian Ground Forces|Russian army]]. In 2000 she published ''Pandrioszka'', an account of life in contemporary Russia.<ref name=romance/> Her 2007 book ''Głową o mur Kremla'' ("Banging one's head against the wall of the Kremlin"),<ref name=romance/> a history of Russia from the 1980s to the present, earned her the nickname ''the Polish [[Anna Politkovskaya|Politkovskaya]]'' (''Polska Politkowska'').{{fact|date=December 2008}}

Kurczab-Redlich received the [[Kazimierz Dziewanowski]] Award for her work as a foreign correspondent and the [[Melchior Wańkowicz]] Award for her reports from Chechnya. In 2005 the Chechen organization [[Echo of War]], along with [[Amnesty International]] and the [[Helsinki Foundation for Human Rights]], nominated her for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].<ref name=romance/>

