{{about|the 2012 Canadian documentary|other films with similar titles|Last Chance (disambiguation)}} {{italic title}} '''''Last Chance''''' (French: '''''Une derniere chance''''') is a 2012 documentary by [[Paul-Émile d'Entremont]] about five [[LGBT]] people seeking the [[right of asylum]] in Canada in order to escape persecution or [[homophobic violence]] in their homelands. Subjects in the film include a transgender woman who was institutionalized by her family in Lebanon, an LGBT person jailed in Egypt, as well as Trudi, a Jamaican lesbian who was "[[Corrective rape|correctively raped]]" at gunpoint. ''Last Chance'' was produced by the [[National Film Board of Canada]].<ref name="Takeuchi">{{cite news|url=https://www.straight.com/article-849216/vancouver/nfb-documentary-follows-queer-refugees-seeking-last-chance-canada|title=NFB documentary follows queer refugees seeking Last Chance in Canada|last=Takeuchi|first=Craig|date=5 December 2012|work=[[Georgia Straight]]|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="Burnett">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.montrealgazette.com/2012/12/07/award-winning-doc-on-queer-refugees-fleeing-to-canada-screening-for-free-on-nfb-website/|title=Award-winning doc on queer refugees fleeing to Canada screening for free on NFB website|last=Burnett|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Burnett|date=7 December 2012|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="Chainney">{{cite news|url=http://www.lapresse.ca/cinema/201212/03/01-4600321-une-derniere-chance-le-combat-des-demandeurs-dasile-gai.php|title=Une dernière chance: le combat des demandeurs d'asile gai|last=Chainney|first=Annik|date=3 December 2012|work=[[La Presse (Canada)]]|publisher=[[Canadian Press]]|language=French|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref>
D'Entremont conceived the idea for the film while in Jordan, working on his previous film, ''Reema, aller-retour''. The film took ten years to make, including three years of [[principal photography]]. Trudi's was the last story to be filmed. Montreal immigration and refugee lawyer Noel St. Pierre was also among those interviewed in the film.<ref name="Burnett"/>
==Release== The film premiered at the 2012 [[Atlantic Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/film-dealing-with-persecution-of-gays-to-be-available-on-nfb-website-1.1065806|title=Film dealing with persecution of gays to be available on NFB website|date=4 December 2012|work=[[Canadian Press]]|publisher=[[CTV News]]|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref> It was also streamed free of charge at [[NFB.ca]] from December 7 to 9, 2012, to mark [[Human Rights Day]].<ref name="Burnett"/><ref name="Chainney"/> Awards for the film include the La Vague/Léonard Forest award for best medium- or feature-length Acadian film at the Festival international du cinéma francophone en Acadie in Moncton, New Brunswick.<ref name="Obenson">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/in-honor-of-human-rights-day-the-nfb-makes-award-winning-feature-doc-last-chance-free-online|title=n Honor of Human Rights Day, The NFB Makes Award-Winning Feature Doc 'Last Chance' Free Online|last=Obenson|first=Tambay A.|date=26 November 2012|work=Indiewire|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref>
